description:
Cross-file code smell: In lichen_lora_l2_deinit() lines 589-592:

    k_mutex_lock(&lora_mutex, K_FOREVER);
    lora_state.rx_callback = NULL;
    lora_state.rx_callback_user_data = NULL;
    k_mutex_unlock(&lora_mutex);

This acquires lora_mutex after it was just reinitialized (line 575). The comment says 'This must happen AFTER mutex reinitialization so we have a valid mutex to lock.'

However:
1. The mutex was just reinitialized - no one else can be holding it
2. initialized was already cleared atomically (line 540), blocking new operations
3. The RX thread was already joined (line 514), so no callbacks can be in flight

The mutex lock/unlock is unnecessary and potentially misleading - it suggests concurrent access is possible when it isn't (at this point in deinit).

Location: lora_l2.c:589-592

Priority: P4 - cosmetic, the code is correct but the mutex operation is cargo-cult.
